     <p><strong><p><strong>Scott Soames, <em>The Analytic Tradition in Philosophy Volume 3: The Struggle for Modality</em>, Princeton University Press, 2025, 352pp., $65.00 (hbk) ISBN 9780691160047.</strong></p></strong></p>
     <p><strong>Reviewed by Fraser MacBride, University of Manchester</strong></p>
     <p>It was a struggle, but commonsense won out. That’s not my verdict on Scott Soames’ <em>The Struggle for Modality</em>.<sup><a href="applewebdata://3B8A561E-3592-4430-96D0-483EE8E7C7E9#_edn1" name="_ednref1" title="">[1]</a></sup> That’s his verdict on the development of analytic philosophy <em>vis-à-vis</em> our understanding of modality—a developmental arc described by Soames which culminates in our community embrace of metaphysical modality, specifically the distinction of essence and accident <em>in re</em>. We began benighted because we made a crippling identification of necessity with analyticity and because we lacked a developed modal logic—the lack being partly a consequence of the crippling identification already made. Modal logic didn’t come of age until Kripke published his model-theoretic semantics for modal logic in the early 60s. But that wasn’t itself the decisive breakthrough because models need to be interpreted.</p> <p>What was...
